body: Would you be able to share the model and the commit you used to build the product off?

@yuslepukhin
Met the same problem.
I have tested ORT-1.3.0, 1.4.0 and 1.5.2 with python & c++.
Here is my model and image. https://drive.google.com/file/d/1XpLTfNpqEdBVi1glnHFtMDvdDT38C7Tn/view?usp=sharing
Here is my python code.
```
import onnxruntime
import cv2
import torch
sess = onnxruntime.InferenceSession('./test.onnx')
inputs = cv2.imread('1.jpg')
inputs = cv2.resize(inputs, (800,1067))
inputs = torch.as_tensor(inputs.astype('float32').transpose(2,0,1))
inputs = inputs.unsqueeze(0)
for i in range(100):
    res = sess.run(None, {sess.get_inputs()[0].name:inputs.numpy()})
    print (res[0].shape[0])
```

@yuslepukhin Is this bug fixed? I want to share some information. I compared params ’Training‘ in tensorflow dropout,
| params/results  | Run 1 times with 1 session | Run many times with 1 session |
| ----------------|:---------------:| --------:|
| Training=True  | diff  | diff  |
| Training=False | same | diff  |

@zhuxiaoxuhit The issue title uses the term `stable`, however, later in the comment you mention the same results. We can't guarantee the latter with the floating point arithmetic. Looking at the chart you published it looks very similar with some time shift. What is your tolerance? We often can not produce more precision than 3 digits after decimal point.
Some output examples would be helpful.

issue.body:
**Describe the bug**
 I created session once, then made inferences with same input repeatedly, but got different results.
Maybe the problem is same to #5600 

**System information**
- OS Platform and Distribution (e.g., Linux Ubuntu 16.04): Linux Ubuntu 16.04 & Windows 10
- ONNX Runtime installed from (source or binary): binary
- ONNX Runtime version: 1.3.0 1.4.0 1.5.2
- Python version: 3.7
- Visual Studio version (if applicable): 2017
- GCC/Compiler version (if compiling from source):
- CUDA/cuDNN version: CUDA 10.1 / cuDNN 7.6.3
- GPU model and memory: 2080ti 16G

**To Reproduce**
- Describe steps/code to reproduce the behavior.
- Attach the ONNX model to the issue (where applicable) to expedite investigation.
Here is the model and test image. https://drive.google.com/file/d/1XpLTfNpqEdBVi1glnHFtMDvdDT38C7Tn/view?usp=sharing
Here is my code.
```
import onnxruntime
import cv2
import torch
sess = onnxruntime.InferenceSession('./test.onnx')
inputs = cv2.imread('1.jpg')
inputs = cv2.resize(inputs, (800,1067))
inputs = torch.as_tensor(inputs.astype('float32').transpose(2,0,1))
inputs = inputs.unsqueeze(0)
for i in range(100):
    res = sess.run(None, {sess.get_inputs()[0].name:inputs.numpy()})
    print (res[0].shape[0])
```

**Expected behavior**
Get same results everytime inference.

**Screenshots**
![2](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/26213470/97941146-cf123200-1dbe-11eb-8270-37b55719bb8a.png)

body:
@yuslepukhin 
Thank u ^-^
"STABLE" means that: 
"create session one time, then do inference many times with the same input -> get same results."
but now we got different results, I want to konw y. I read source code and didn't find the reason, this is the first question.
The second is aboout dropout. When I use dropout in inference,    I find method "RandomUniform::Compute()" in "onnxruntime/core/providers/cpu/generator/random.cc" is called, but  "onnxruntime/core/providers/cpu/nn/dropout_op.h"  is not called.  I wnat to know how dropout_op works and how to modify the value of seed in c++ api. 
```python
sess = onnxruntime.InferenceSession('./test.onnx')
inputs = cv2.imread('1.jpg')
inputs = cv2.resize(inputs, (800,1067))
inputs = torch.as_tensor(inputs.astype('float32').transpose(2,0,1))
inputs = inputs.unsqueeze(0)
for i in range(100):
    res = sess.run(None, {sess.get_inputs()[0].name:inputs.numpy()})
```

Here is the documentation for [Dropout](https://github.com/onnx/onnx/blob/master/docs/Operators.md#Dropout).
If you run it in training mode, there will be a randomized dropout.  In inference mode  where output is a copy of the input nothing is dropped out and our optimizer eliminates Dropout node from the execution graph. So if you are running an inference, the issue is probably not in the dropout.

I have not answered your question fully. Seed is an attribute of Dropout and as such it is a part of the serialized model, which is protobuf. At runtime, attributes are const. If you want to modify it you would have to edit the model and protobuf has many APIs to accomplish that, including python and C++.
@yuslepukhin have you tried this on gpu? It is stable on cpu. The problem will be happen only under gpu mode.
@freedenS This specific ticket talks about differences on CPU. Although the example is yours, I would appreciate the feedback from @zhuxiaoxuhit.
